<exercises xml:id="ex-InterpretingDerivatives">
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following functions, use the definition of the derivative at a point to find <m>f'(a)</m> and then find the equation of the line tangent to the graph of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x=a</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Remember: The equation of a line given the slope <m>m</m> and <m>(x_1, y_1)</m>, a point on the line is <m>y=m(x-x_1)+y_1</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = x^2+x-1</m> with <m>a=0</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f'(0) \amp = 1</mrow>
                        <mrow>y \amp = x-1</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = x^3+1</m> with <m>a=2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f'(2) \amp = 12</mrow>
                        <mrow>y \amp = 12x-15</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = \dfrac{2}{\sqrt{x}}</m> with <m>a=6</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f'(6) \amp = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y \amp = -\frac{x}{6\sqrt{6}}+\frac{3}{\sqrt{6}}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = \sqrt{3x-1}</m> with <m>a=2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f'(2) \amp = \dfrac{3}{2\sqrt{5}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y \amp = -\frac{3x}{2\sqrt{5}}+\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = x-x^2</m> with <m>a=2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f'(2) \amp = -3</mrow>
                        <mrow>y \amp = -3x+4</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = \dfrac{x}{x+1}</m> with <m>a=1</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f'(1) \amp = \frac{1}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y \amp = \frac{x}{4} + \frac{1}{4}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                We start watching a car driving down a straight road towards a stop sign. We can tell that their position function is <m>s(t) = -7.5t^2 + 81t</m> with position measured in feet from their location when we began observing them and time measured in seconds.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How fast is the car driving at <m>t=0</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>v(0)=s'(0)=81</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How fast is the car driving at <m>t=2</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>v(2) = s'(2)=36</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    At what value of <m>t</m> does the car stop (their velocity is 0)?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>t=5.4</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How far did they travel before they stopped?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>s(5.4)-s(0)=396.9</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    At <m>t=0</m> what is the acceleration of the car?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>a(0)=v'(0)=-15</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    At <m>t=2</m> what is the acceleration of the car?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>a(2)=v'(2)=-15</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                The monetary value of an ancient mathematical artifact (the pencil that Isaac Barrow used to prove the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus in 1667) follows the function <m>m(t) = \sqrt{1600t}+10</m> where <m>t</m> is the number of years since 1667 and <m>m(t)</m> is the monetary value of the pencil in US Dollars.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What was the overall change in value from 1667 to 1967 (from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=300)</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>m(300)-m(0)\approx \$292.82</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What was the average rate of change of the value from 1667 to 1967?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{m(300)-m(0)}{300-0} \approx \$0.98</m>/year
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What was the instantaneous rate of change of the value in 1967?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>m'(300)\approx \$1.55</m>/year
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find <m>m(354)</m> and <m>m'(354)</m>, and interpret both of these values.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>m(354)\approx \$762.60</m> is the value of the pencil 354 years after 1667 (in 2021).
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>m'(354)\approx \$1.06</m> is the rate of change in the value of the pencil 354 years after 1667 (in 2021). This means that in 2021, we expect the price to increase at a rate of $1.06/year.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use <m>m(354)</m> and <m>m'(354)</m> to approximate the value of the pencil in 2022.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>m(354)+m'(354)\approx \$763.66</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use <m>m(t)</m> to find the value in 2022. Was the approximation close or not? Explain.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>m(355)\approx \$763.66</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
</exercises>